        "# Credit Card Fraud Detection\n",
        "\n",
        "Fraud modeling is hard for a practical reason: the transactions you care about are rare, the losses can be large, and many legitimate transactions also look irregular in the raw data. Travel, holiday spending, or an unusually large purchase can resemble fraud unless the model has enough context to tell the difference.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Card-present frauds\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Card-present (CP) fraud occurs when a transaction is made using a **physical credit card** that has been lost, stolen, counterfeited, or intercepted.\n",
        "-   The legitimate cardholder is typically unaware of the fraudulent use until they notice unauthorized transactions on their statement or are alerted by their bank.\n",
        "-   What makes CP fraud distinct is that the **physical card** is used at the point of sale (e.g., a retail store or restaurant).\n",
        "\n",
        "## Card-not-present frauds\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Card-not-present (CNP) fraud occurs when credit card information (such as card number, expiry date, CVV) is used **without** the physical card being present.\n",
        "-   This type of fraud is common in online purchases.\n",
        "-   Fraudsters may obtain card details through data breaches, phishing scams, or malware.\n",
        "-   CNP fraud has become increasingly prevalent with the growth of e-commerce.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Credit Card Fraud Detection Systems (CCFDS)\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Credit Card Fraud Detection Systems (CCFDS)** score transactions in real-time or near real-time using signals such as amount, merchant or terminal history, timing, location, and recent customer activity.\n",
        "-   If the risk score is high enough, the system may decline the payment, ask the cardholder to confirm it, or route the case to a fraud analyst.\n",
        "-   The tradeoff is simple to describe and hard to manage: every missed fraud loses money, while every false positive interrupts a legitimate customer.\n",
        "-   Those decisions usually have to be made under tight latency limits, so the system has to be fast enough for the payment flow and accurate enough to justify intervention.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Class Imbalance in Fraud Detection\n",
        "\n",
        "Fraud is rare in most transaction streams. The harder issue is that the non-fraud class is not clean or homogeneous: it includes routine purchases, travel spending, seasonal spikes, emergency purchases, and other behavior that is unusual but still legitimate.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Characteristics in Fraud Data**\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Rarity of Fraud: Fraudulent transactions are usually a small fraction (often $< 1\\%$, sometimes $< 0.1\\%$) of total transactions.\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Standard accuracy can be misleading; a model that predicts \"no fraud\" for every transaction can still look excellent on accuracy alone.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Impact of Sample Size**\n",
        "\n",
        "The difficulty of modeling depends on both the imbalance ratio (IR) and the absolute number of fraud cases.\n",
        "\n",
        "A higher imbalance ratio (IR) indicates greater class imbalance: $$IR = \\frac{\\text{Number of samples in majority class}}{\\text{Number of samples in minority class}}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The absolute number of samples in the minority class (fraud) also matters:\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Large Datasets:** A low fraud rate (e.g., 0.1%) in a large dataset (e.g., 100 million transactions) can still yield enough fraud examples (e.g., 100,000) to train and test a model sensibly.\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Small Datasets:** The same low fraud rate in a small dataset (e.g., 1,000 transactions) leaves you with very few fraud examples (approximately 1 fraud case if the rate is 0.1%). That is usually not enough for reliable training or evaluation.\n",
        "\n",
        "In the rest of the lab, assume a large dataset with enough fraud cases to fit models, but still with the severe class imbalance seen in production.\n",
        "\n",
