    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Class-Sensitive Evaluation Approach\n",
        "\n",
        "**Rationale:**\n",
        "\n",
        "-   In fraud detection, the positive class (fraud) is much rarer than the negative class (legitimate transactions).\n",
        "-   **ROC-AUC** is still a useful broad, threshold-free ranking and discrimination diagnostic:\n",
        "    -   ROC-AUC summarizes how well the model ranks fraud above legitimate transactions across all possible decision thresholds.\n",
        "    -   It is familiar, easy to benchmark, and helpful for comparing broad ranking quality across challenger models.\n",
        "    -   However, it should not be the primary or sole success metric in highly imbalanced fraud detection.\n",
        "    -   ROC plots the True Positive Rate (TPR, recall) against the False Positive Rate (FPR) at different decision thresholds.\n",
        "    -   FPR is calculated as $\\frac{\\text{False Positives}}{\\text{All Actual Negatives}}$. When the legitimate class is very large, even a low FPR can still correspond to an operationally unacceptable number of false alerts.\n",
        "-   **Precision-Recall (PR) curves** are often better aligned with rare-event fraud operations:\n",
        "    -   The PR curve plots Precision ($\\frac{\\text{TP}}{\\text{TP} + \\text{FP}}$) against Recall ($\\frac{\\text{TP}}{\\text{TP} + \\text{FN}}$).\n",
        "    -   Precision directly measures how many of the predicted frauds are actually fraud, which is critical when investigating alerts.\n",
        "    -   PR curves do not account for true negatives, making them more sensitive to the model's performance on the minority class.\n",
        "-   **PR-AUC** (Area Under the PR Curve, also called Average Precision or AP) summarizes the PR curve in a single number.\n",
        "    -   A high PR-AUC means the model can achieve both high precision and high recall for fraud detection.\n",
        "    -   The baseline (random classifier) PR-AUC equals the prevalence of the positive class, making it easier to assess model quality.\n",
        "-   **Operational metrics** still matter for deployment:\n",
        "    -   Precision at top-$k$ or top-$x\\%$\n",
        "    -   Recall at fixed review capacity\n",
        "    -   Dollar-weighted capture or savings\n",
        "    -   False positives per true positive\n",
        "    -   Calibration diagnostics\n",
        "\n",
        "PR-AUC and AP are conceptually similar, but AP calculates the area under the PR curve using the observed precision values at each threshold rather than an interpolated curve. Industry practice is not \"never use ROC-AUC\"; rather, ROC-AUC is a useful secondary diagnostic but is insufficient on its own for highly imbalanced fraud problems. In this lab, we use AP (`average_precision`) as the primary model-selection metric while keeping ROC-AUC as a secondary ranking diagnostic. For details, please refer to the scikit-learn documentation on [Average Precision](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.average_precision_score.html#sklearn.metrics.average_precision_score).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Process:**\n",
        "\n",
        "1.  Train multiple estimators on the original, imbalanced dataset.\n",
        "2.  Select the best model using **average precision** as the primary metric while keeping the top three non-weighted-ensemble learners from the tuning leaderboard in view.\n",
        "3.  Calibrate the selected best model's decision threshold on the full tuning split with AutoGluon's native F1 objective.\n",
        "4.  Evaluate the selected predictor on the test set under both the default and optimized thresholds using AP, ROC-AUC, and the operational metrics most relevant to the fraud workflow.\n",
        "5.  After the threshold is fixed, inspect the shortlisted base models on one test-set calibration plot as a descriptive diagnostic.\n",
        "\n",
        "Setup AutoGluon parameters."
