        "## Resampling Approach\n",
        "\n",
        "**Rationale:**\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Class-based resampling techniques modify the training data's class distribution to create a less extreme dataset for model fitting.\n",
        "-   Resampling is performed **only** on the training data.\n",
        "-   The tuning and test sets remain in their original, imbalanced form to reflect reality (i.e., fraud is rare).\n",
        "-   In fraud detection, the model still needs plenty of legitimate transactions in view. The job is to learn fraud patterns without hiding the wide range of legitimate behavior that can look suspicious at first glance.\n",
        "\n",
        "A fully balanced 1:1 sample is often a bad default for fraud detection because it creates a training world the business never sees in production. Fraud is rare, legitimate traffic is abundant, and some legitimate customers will always look odd in the raw data.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why 1:1 is usually a poor statistical default**\n",
        "\n",
        "-   It throws away too much useful non-fraud information. Legitimate transactions contain customer, merchant, device, geographic, seasonal, and amount variation that helps define the real non-fraud population.\n",
        "-   It can inflate false positives because the sampled data teaches the model that fraud is much more common than it really is unless later calibration, weighting, or prior correction is applied.\n",
        "-   It damages probability calibration. The rank ordering may still be useful, but raw predicted fraud probabilities from a 1:1 sample are usually not business-usable without correction.\n",
        "-   More non-fraud controls usually improve precision because they help the model distinguish fraud from legitimate weirdness. The gains are often largest when moving from 1:1 toward ratios such as 5:1 or 10:1.\n",
        "-   It can make the model learn sampling artifacts if the undersampled non-fraud group no longer looks like the real production population.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why 1:1 is usually a poor business default**\n",
        "\n",
        "-   False positives are expensive: they can create declined legitimate transactions, manual review cost, customer frustration, merchant friction, and lost revenue.\n",
        "-   The business does not operate in a 50% fraud world. The model must prioritize the riskiest cases inside a large sea of legitimate activity.\n",
        "-   Fraud teams have limited alert capacity, so the model must rank cases well on a realistic population rather than on an artificially balanced slice.\n",
        "-   Many legitimate transactions look suspicious. The business wants to separate fraud from legitimate weirdness, not just from a tiny puddle of non-fraud examples.\n",
        "\n",
        "A practical compromise is to reduce the imbalance without pretending fraud and non-fraud are equally common:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Non-fraud:Fraud ratio | Why it is useful |\n",
        "|---|---|\n",
        "| `5:1` | Useful when fraud cases are limited and model training cost matters, but it is still a relatively aggressive rebalance. |\n",
        "| `10:1` | Strong general-purpose default for rare-event modeling. |\n",
        "| `20:1` | Better when legitimate behavior is highly diverse and cheap to include. |\n",
        "| `1:1` | Usually too artificial for deployment-oriented fraud modeling; keep it as a classroom simplification rather than a default. |\n",
        "\n",
        "**Common Resampling Schemes:**\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Random Undersampling (RUS):** Randomly remove instances from the majority class until the class imbalance is less extreme. In practice, a moderate target such as 5:1, 10:1, or 20:1 is often preferable to forcing a 1:1 sample. This can lead to loss of information from the majority class. However, the scheme substantially reduces the dataset size, which can be beneficial for training speed and memory usage.\n",
        "-   **Random Oversampling (ROS):** Randomly duplicate instances from the minority class. Here too, a moderate target such as 5:1, 10:1, or 20:1 is often safer than a 1:1 sample. This can lead to overfitting on the minority class examples.\n",
        "-   **SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique):** Creates synthetic samples for the minority class by interpolating between actual minority instances. This can help to create a more diverse set of minority examples than simple oversampling.\n",
        "-   **Hybrid Methods:** Combine oversampling and undersampling. For example, first apply SMOTE to generate synthetic samples for the minority class, then apply random undersampling to the majority class.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Shared workflow:**\n",
        "\n",
        "Each resampling strategy below changes only the training data. The repeated workflow then fits AutoGluon on the resampled sample, keeps the top three non-ensemble base models from the tuning leaderboard, uses `top_base_models_sX[0]` as the selected base learner, lets AutoGluon calibrate an F1-maximizing decision threshold on the full tuning data, compares default and optimized thresholds on the test set, and ends with one held-out test-set calibration plot for the top base models only.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Random Undersampling (RUS)\n",
        "\n",
        "Randomly remove instances from the majority class to reduce the imbalance in the training set. In this lab, 10:1 is the default example, 5:1 is a more aggressive option when fraud cases are limited and training cost matters, and 20:1 is a more conservative option when legitimate behavior is highly diverse.\n",
        "\n",
        "Setting the ratio to 1:1 is usually a bad idea for fraud data because it discards too many legitimate transactions, narrows the model's view of normal-but-unusual behavior, and can make the fitted boundary depend on a small and potentially unrepresentative slice of non-fraud cases. That can hurt precision and increase false positives after deployment."
      ],
      "id": "3b424592"
    },
