      "source": [
        "### Prior Correction for Logistic Regression After Class-Based Resampling\n",
        "\n",
        "When a logistic regression is fit on a class-resampled version of the training set, the fitted probabilities live on the resampled class-prior scale rather than the original training-set scale. For random undersampling or random oversampling, if the sampling depends only on the class label and does not otherwise change the conditional feature distributions $P(X \\mid Y=1)$ and $P(X \\mid Y=0)$, then the slope coefficients are preserved and only the intercept changes.\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "-   $\\hat\\pi_\\text{original}$ = `prior_original`, the fraud rate in the original non-resampled training set.\n",
        "-   $\\hat\\pi_\\text{sampled}$ = `prior_resampled`, the fraud rate in the class-resampled training set.\n",
        "-   $\\widehat{\\alpha}_\\text{sampled}$ = `intercept_hat_resampled`, the intercept from a logistic regression fit on the sampled training set.\n",
        "-   $\\widehat{\\beta}_\\text{sampled}$ = the slope vector from the same sampled-data fit.\n",
        "\n",
        "Write the sampled-data linear predictor as\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat{\\eta}_\\text{sampled}(x)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\widehat{\\alpha}_\\text{sampled}\n",
        "+\n",
        "x^\\top \\widehat{\\beta}_\\text{sampled}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "If class-1 observations are retained or duplicated by a class-specific factor $c_1$ and class-0 observations by a factor $c_0$, then class-based sampling implies\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{P_\\text{sampled}(Y=1 \\mid X=x)}{P_\\text{sampled}(Y=0 \\mid X=x)}\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{c_1}{c_0}\n",
        "\\cdot\n",
        "\\frac{P_\\text{original}(Y=1 \\mid X=x)}{P_\\text{original}(Y=0 \\mid X=x)}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore the sampled and original log-odds differ by a constant:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat{\\eta}_\\text{original}(x)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\widehat{\\eta}_\\text{sampled}(x)\n",
        "-\n",
        "\\log\\left(\\frac{c_1}{c_0}\\right).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The same constant can be written in terms of the two marginal class odds because\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\log\\left(\\frac{c_1}{c_0}\\right)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\operatorname{logit}(\\hat\\pi_\\text{sampled})\n",
        "-\n",
        "\\operatorname{logit}(\\hat\\pi_\\text{original}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Substituting gives the post-fit prior correction:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat{\\eta}_\\text{original}(x)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\widehat{\\eta}_\\text{sampled}(x)\n",
        "+\n",
        "\\operatorname{logit}(\\hat\\pi_\\text{original})\n",
        "-\n",
        "\\operatorname{logit}(\\hat\\pi_\\text{sampled}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Equivalently, only the intercept changes:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat{\\alpha}_\\text{original}\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\widehat{\\alpha}_\\text{sampled}\n",
        "+\n",
        "\\operatorname{logit}(\\hat\\pi_\\text{original})\n",
        "-\n",
        "\\operatorname{logit}(\\hat\\pi_\\text{sampled}),\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\widehat{\\beta}_\\text{original}\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\widehat{\\beta}_\\text{sampled}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The corrected fitted probability on the original training-set prior scale is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat{P}_\\text{original}(Y=1 \\mid X=x)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{1}{1+\\exp\\{-\\widehat{\\eta}_\\text{original}(x)\\}}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For fraud data, $\\hat\\pi_\\text{original}$ is usually much smaller than $\\hat\\pi_\\text{sampled}$. Therefore the correction term is usually negative, lowering the intercept and pulling predicted probabilities back toward the original non-resampled training-set fraud rate.\n",
        "\n",
        "Do not use `sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression` for this demonstration. Its default fit uses L2 regularization and the LBFGS solver, whereas the derivation here is meant to align with an unpenalized binomial GLM fit with `statsmodels` via IRLS."
      ],
